    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d7dd2e6d-07ce-4277-bbd4-3adffb81b9e9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 35-year-old male who presents to the infectious disease clinic appearing visibly fatigued and underweight. He is pale, with sunken eyes and mild temporal wasting, wearing a loose-fitting jacket that no longer fits his slender frame. He speaks softly and is frequently interrupted by a persistent, productive cough that he attempts to suppress with a tissue. His skin shows faint hyperpigmented patches, and he has mild cervical lymphadenopathy palpable on examination.\n\n{patientName} works as a freelance graphic designer from home, spending long hours in front of a screen. He lives alone in a small urban apartment and maintains a limited social circle, largely due to increasing fatigue and social stigma related to his HIV diagnosis. He enjoys sketching, watching documentaries, and cooking — although his appetite has declined significantly over the past two months.\n\nHe was diagnosed with HIV four years ago after presenting with a flu-like illness and was initially started on antiretroviral therapy (ART), but he admits to periods of non-adherence due to financial constraints and depressive episodes. He has been smoking half a pack of cigarettes daily for over a decade and occasionally uses cannabis. He consumes alcohol socially but denies intravenous drug use.\n\nOver the past six weeks, {patientName} has experienced drenching night sweats, low-grade fever, worsening productive cough with occasional blood-tinged sputum, progressive weight loss (~8 kg over two months), and increasing breathlessness on exertion. He initially attributed the symptoms to a common cold but presented after a family member insisted he seek care.\n\nOn examination, his temperature is elevated at 38.6 °C, and he weighs only 57 kg. Lung auscultation reveals coarse crackles at the left upper lobe. Chest imaging and microbiological workup confirmed pulmonary tuberculosis superimposed on his HIV disease, consistent with ICD-10 B20.0. He is now being admitted for initiation of anti-tubercular therapy and ART optimization."
          }
        ]
